pd.read_html()

to fetch table data. To fix this, please refer to the link here.

import os, ssl

getattr(ssl, '_create_unverified_context', None)):

Obtaining Historical Data: DIA and It's Components¶

We scraped the DJIA Wikipedia page for the 30 companies that make it consists of and save it to a data frame called "dow_companies" after adjusting data types and renaming some columns. Although we are using the DIA ETF, this ETF's holdings are exactly those 30 companies that make up the DJIA!

Note that DIA holds a total of 32 positions (including U.S. Dollar), but for the purposes of this project we will be excluding U.S. dollar and Kyndryl Holdings Inc (KD), since the latter just began public trading on Nov. 4th, 2021 (won't have enough data for us to work with). The full list of DIA holdings can be downloaded from the website here under the section "Holdings".

This is what our data frame looks like:

In [3]:
# The table we need when we need when we scraped the website 
# for tabular data is in position 1 of the list that 
# pd.read_html automatically assigns it to:
dow_companies = pd.read_html('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dow_Jones_Industrial_Average')[1]

# We need all rows, but just the first 5 columns
dow_companies = dow_companies.iloc[:,:5].copy()

# Do not want whitespace in column name
dow_companies.rename(columns = {"Date added":"Date_Added", "Symbol":"Ticker"}, inplace = True)

# Changing the datatype specifically to "datetime64" rather than just "object" (text)
dow_companies.Date_Added = pd.to_datetime(dow_companies.Date_Added)

# Adding all tickers to a list for later use
ticker_list = dow_companies.Ticker.to_list()

# Saving it to a .csv file for future use
dow_companies.to_csv('dow_companies_info.csv', index = False) # drop index with 0-29

Afterwards, we used the yfinance library to fetch historical data of the DIA ETF.

In short, "DIA is the ETF for investors seeking to replicate the performance of the Dow" (Investopedia). DIA's holdings consists of the 30 companies that make up the DJIA.

For the purposes of this project, just grabbing the past ~15 years of data should suffice. After we obtained the data we assigned the data frame to "dia".

We also created a copy of the "dia" data frame that only contains it's closing prices and assigned it to "dia__close_price_only".

The closing price column for the DIA ETF should show up on the very right of "df":

Normalizing Data¶

From the graph above - we actually can't make much out of it because all stocks are starting out at a different price. In order to make the data more meaningful and determine if a stock performs well or not we need to normalize the prices of all stocks to a common base value (i.e. $100).

More about normalizing prices here and here.

We will normalize the prices by doing the following:

  1. Divide each and every row by the first row (where we have the starting data and thus, starting prices for stocks in our given timestamp). We should get 1 for the very first row after we've done this.

  2. Multiply prices by 100 (common initial base value).

So now, all our stock prices start at $100 and depending on the individual performance, the stocks (and the DIA ETF), end at their respective values - which is now easier to compare.

Our normalized data frame, assigned to "normalized" is shown below:

In [8]:
# divide every row by the first row
# and multiply by 100
normalized = df.div(df.iloc[0])*100

If we want to compare any of the 30 companies in DIA with each other, and with the DIA ETF - I've created a function called "compare_companies_with_DIA" that takes as many companies as you want to comapre (as long as they're in DIA) with each other.

For example, let's say I want to just compare Apple and Microsoft with the DIA ETF, I would input their tickers as such:

compare_companies_with_DIA('AAPL','MSFT')

Note that capitalization of the tickers matter here!

In [11]:
def compare_companies_with_DIA(*args):
    plot = normalized[['DIA_ETF', *args]].plot(figsize = (20,12), 
                                               fontsize = 15)
    
    plt.ylabel('Prices ($)', fontsize = 20)
    plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize = 20)
    plt.title('Compared to DIA ETF', fontsize = 25)
    plt.legend(fontsize = 20)
    plt.show()

compare_companies_with_DIA('AAPL','MSFT')



Annual Return and Annual Volatility¶

The above charts all still use the absolute prices of the stock which does not say much own it's own. In order to better see how an investment's return compares to other similar investments, we want to use daily returns.

We can calculate daily returns (percent change in prices) using the formula:

$$\Large \%_{change} = \frac{P_{f}-P_{i}}{P_{i}} * 100 $$

Where $P_{f}$ is the final price and $P_{i}$ is the initial price.

The percentage change in daily prices can be calculated simply by using the .pct_change( ) method which computes the percentage change from the immediately previous row by default. We'll add the new data frame with the daily returns to "daily_returns".

Note: even we already used pct_change( ) to calculate the change, python has not yet multiplied by 100 so we would have to do that manually in our code.

In [12]:
daily_returns = df.pct_change()*100 # manually multiplying by 100

daily_returns

Now that we have our daily percent changes, we will find the annual returns and annual volatility using the .agg( ) method and adding the data into a new data frame called "return_and_volatility":

  • For annual returns we get the mean, and then multiply it by 252.

The annual return can be calculated by using the equation:

$$\large \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_{i}}{n} * 252$$

Where:

  • $x_{i}$ is each day
  • $n$ is the total number of days

  • $252$ is the estimated number of trading days in a year

  • For annual volatility, we sum up the daily percent change and get the standard deviation, and then multiply it by the square root of 252.

The annual volatility (standard deviation) can be calculated by using the equation:

$$\Large \sigma_{annual} = \sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_{i} - \mu)^2}{n}} * \sqrt{252}$$

Where:

  • $\sigma$ is the standard deviation/ volatility
  • $n$ is the size of the population (number of days in total)
  • $x_{i}$ is each value from the population (each daily return)
  • $\mu$ is the population mean (annual return)
  • $252$ is the number of estimated trading days in a year

"Volatility represents how large an asset's prices swing around the mean priceit is a statistical measure of its dispersion of returns." - Investopedia

Useful Information Regarding Volatility:

  • How to Calculate Annualized Volatility

  • Why Is Volatility Proportional to the Square Root of Time?

Volatility is also a measure of active risk.

Index Tracking Intro¶

Before diving into the index tracking portion, we need to understand here that indexes, index funds, and exchange traded funds are not the same thing.

  • An Introduction to U.S. Stock Market Indexes
  • Difference Between Indexes and Index Funds
  • Difference Between Index Funds and ETFs

Although we can invest directly into DIA since it is an ETF, let's say we don't want to pay the expense ratio for whatever reason. The DIA ETF expense ratio as of Nov. 9th, 2021 is 0.16% annually.

Here is an example of the expense ratio according to Investopedia:

The Vanguard S&P 500 ETF (ticker: VOO), an index fund that replicates the Standard & Poor's (S&P) 500 Index, has one of the lowest expense ratios in the industry at 0.03% annually. At this level, investors are charged just \$3 per year for every $10,000 invested.

So, we're going to track the DIA ETF (which in turn replicates the DJIA Index). To keep things simple moving forward, since we are technically tracking the DJIA index anyways through tracking DIA, we'll just say we're tracking the DJIA Index. Also I'm going to use DIA and DJIA interchangeably, but just know that they both mean the same thing for now.

Remember that you can't invest in the DJIA Index itself!

The Plan¶

We're going to track the DJIA using a subset of only 10 stocks (from DJIA) because we are too broke to afford more than 10 and do not want to pay the DIA ETF expense ratio.

The criteria in choosing which specific 10 stocks to include in our tracking portfolio will be to look at those with the lowest individual tracking error (TE). We will calculate the TE in our training/ fitting period.

  • Training Period: 2017 & 2018
  • Forward Testing Period: 2019

We're going to fit the parameters of our portfolio to the data in the training period (2 years). This doesn't guarantee that the tracking portfolio does a good job on new data so we will forward test our tracking portfolio's ability to track the index and use 2019 as the forward test period.

Lastly, once we have identified the 10 stocks to include in our tracking portfolio, we need to find their optimal weights in the portfolio to minimize TE.



First let's select the closing prices of stocks (including DIA) only within 2017 and 2018 and normailze these prices. We will assign this to a new data frame called, "df2_normalized".

We will also create a new data frame for daily returns, only containing the data from 2017 and 2018 - and assign it to "daily_returns2"

Next we need a metric that allows us to measure how well a stock our portfolio tracks the DJIA index (tracking error). In order to calculate an individual stock's tracking error, we have to calculate the return differences between the stock's daily return and the daily returns of the index (in this case DIA). We will save this in a new data frame called "return_difference".

Let's see the data frame as a whole, and the mean and standard deviation (volatility):

In [33]:
# Subtract DIA index's daily returns from

return_difference = daily_returns2.sub(daily_returns2.DIA_ETF, axis = 0)

print('\033[4mreturn_difference Data Frame\033[0m')
display(return_difference)
